  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="justify">I&apos;ve been chatting with several people [a dozen or two] who do research 
on the diurnal practices of producing sci/tech/med knowledge</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="26" relname="span"> and we all 
find the recent discussions on this list about how to talk with scientists 
tragic and comic. </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="16" relname="span"> 

During our own careers as researchers in sci/tech/med studies most of us 
have spent about a quarter to a third of our time in laboratories/clinics.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="volitional-cause">
We could not do our work without talking, all the time, with 
scientists/engineers/clinicians, and they with us.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="16" relname="elaboration">  We always read their 
work and vice versa;</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="16" relname="elaboration"> we discuss our projects at length. </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="20" relname="span"> Among such 
researchers I am NOT atypical at all in giving about a quarter of my 
invited talks to scientists, in being invited regularly to participate 
in conferences organized by scientists, and in that some scientists use 
my work in their courses. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="concession"> I am NOT suggesting that all these people like 
or agree with our work,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="19" relname="span"> but we are most certainly engaged in rich, 
complex conversations with them. </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="21" relname="span"> I would say the same about people 
engaged in policy making and people engaged in education issues;</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="18" relname="span"> that is, 
that they read our research, approach us to talk,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="elaboration"> and we have rich, 
complex conversations with them, not necessarily leading to agreement.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="14" relname="antithesis">
These relationships are not built in a day or in one meeting,</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="24" relname="span"> but the 
process of building them is also not the least bit mysterious. </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="14" relname="elaboration"> I would 
say that &apos;effort&apos; is the keyword and, of course, a complete absence of 
any dominance/submission moves.</segment>
